Midgaard's charter registries cross-reference the Bell Synod in three ledger series: early
oath-certification correspondence, Violet Compact witnessing contracts with a Rakuen satellite
office, and sealed warrant authorizations routing displaced populations through Kel'Shadra
intake. The Continuity faction classifies the Synod as a defunct ecclesiastical institution
under institutional succession law, placing it outside active administrative liability. The
Reckoning faction disputes this framing: the Synod's confession protocols were the legal
mechanism by which Midgaard's resettlement testimonies were absorbed and routed to "below
bell-line; no civic remainder" classification. Midgaard commissioned the upstream displacement;
the Synod provided the downstream disappearance mechanism. Charter jurisdiction prefers
ecclesiastical succession framing because it routes accountability questions into a legal domain
the Continuity faction controls. The jurisdictional classification dispute determines whether
Midgaard's role in the testimony suppression chain carries active legal obligation.

flags KOWLOON
