Kowloon's Neon Covenant governance depends on multi-office signal coordination: no single
district controls the communication infrastructure for all others. The Bell Synod is studied
by the Jade Magistracy as the definitive historical failure of single-office signal control.
When the institution benefiting from suppressing information also controls the system coordinating
emergency response, those functions will eventually conflict—and suppression wins. The Night
of Unsounded Bells is the documented proof case. Kowloon's Black Ledger parallel is acknowledged
internally: if a reform bloc attempted to expose condemned-debtor transfer records, Kowloon's
Continuity equivalent would face the same choice the Synod hardliners faced. The Jade Magistracy's
emergency protocol revision seven years ago prohibited single-office control of inter-district
signal systems. The revision's preamble does not cite the Bell Synod by name, but its drafting
committee's notes do.

