Mafdet's Ledger Houses apply dual-attestation requirements to oath-certified testimony: a
confession or claim carries binding legal weight only when two independent witnesses confirm
it under the same evidentiary standard. The Bell Synod's single-office admission model fails
this requirement categorically. All Synod-certified testimony is therefore legally suspect under
Strandline Compact standards—not inadmissible outright, but requiring counter-certification
before the Swift Court will accept it. This minimum standard was established precisely to prevent
the Bell Synod model from replicating in maritime law. Mafdet's harbor arbitration courts
encounter Kel'Shadra heritage cases when ship manifests reference oath certifications from the
Synod period. Standard disposition is provisional hold pending counter-certification—effectively
indefinite suspension since no counter-certification authority for Synod records currently
exists. The Synod's failure is instructive: oath systems without independent audit become
instruments of whoever controls the intake threshold.

